-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - April 23
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Tue Apr 22, 2014 10:19PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, April 23 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Wednesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Hong Kong's Democratic Party elder Martin Lee Chu-ming has suggested a solution to the deadlock over the 2017 chief executive election that he says would respect the power of the nominating committee while leaving the door open for a pan-democrat candidate. (http://link.reuters.com/jyx68v) -- The move by the mainland's insurance regulator to loosen controls on mergers and acquisitions among Chinese insurers is the first step towards establishing an exit mechanism that will allow weaker players to withdraw from the business through market-driven channels, analysts said. (http://link.reuters.com/kyx68v) -- Beijing has urged the Philippine government to speed up its handling of the fall-out from the 2010 Manila hostage tragedy and to respond to the "legitimate and lawful" demands of the victims' families in Hong Kong. (http://link.reuters.com/pyx68v)  THE STANDARD -- Legislation to protect mainlanders from discrimination may not be necessary as such acts have dropped off considerably in recent weeks, according to the Equal Opportunities Commission in Hong Kong. (http://link.reuters.com/ryx68v) -- The 20,000 yuan daily conversion cap should be lifted when the "Shanghai-Hong Kong Stock Connect" launches in six months, said Financial Services Development Council head Laura Cha Shih May-lung. (http://link.reuters.com/syx68v) -- Cross-border students are being used as couriers to smuggle electronic items. Customs officers at Huanggang say they are tracking the racketeers responsible for the smuggling operations. (http://link.reuters.com/tyx68v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Hong Kong developer Cheung Kong Holdings <0001.HK> said it had generated 300 million yuan ($48.10 million) from sales of all its 150 flats in the latest batch of units on offer in a high-end residential development in Shanghai.MING PAO DAILY  -- Hong Kong's top five property developers had sold an aggregate 7,700 units generating HK$66.5 billion ($8.58 billion) in the past 12 months since the implementation of measures to curb property prices, of which Sun Hung Kai Properties <0016.HK> sold 2,100 units and generated nearly HK$18.6 billion.